name: methyl 3-[bis(methylsulfanyl)methyl]-4-cyano-2-hydroxy-2,5-diphenylcyclopent-3-ene-1-carboxylate
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-1667
Reason: 3-phenyl-2-methyl-2,5-diphenylcyclopent-1-ene has a melting point influenced by functional groups relative to the base melting point of benzene, which is around 5.5°C. The basic unit for comparison is the 1-methyl-2-methylene-2,5-diphenylcyclopent-1-ene moiety, which on its own exhibits intermolecular hydrogen bonding, thus increasing the melting point. The methyl group introduces a rigid structure, which can participate in hydrogen bonding and increase the melting point by approximately +5°C. The two phenyl groups can significantly increase the melting point due to their ability to enhance π-π interactions and overall molecular rigidity. Each phenyl group may contribute around +30 to +50°C. The methylsulfanyl group introduces a rigid structure and a strong withdrawing group, which can increase the melting point by approximately +20°C. The cyano group can participate in hydrogen bonding, raising the melting point by approximately +5°C. The carboxyl group can introduce a hydroxyl group, which can participate in hydrogen bonding, raising the melting point by approximately +5°C. The presence of two additional phenyl groups can significantly increase the melting point due to their ability to enhance π-π interactions and overall molecular rigidity. Each phenyl group may contribute around +30 to +50°C.
